article.headline: Virginia 76, Longwood 57
article.story: Optional. Eds: Virginia 76, Longwood 57. CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- The Cavaliers are going into a break for exams, but coach Dave Leitao gave Friday's performance a failing grade. Leitao certainly isn't handing out A's for effort, either, calling Virginia's 76-57 win over Longwood "probably one of the most uninspiring performances we have had." "I'm not looking at anything that I saw from a positive standpoint or an individual standpoint," Leitao said. "If you have a flat tire on your car, does it matter if it's shiny?" The Cavaliers don't play again until Dec. 19 at home against Hampton. Sean Singletary knows the toll the break can take on his team. "We struggled this time last year, too," Singletary said. "We just need to get back on track because we only have three or four games before ACC play." Singletary finished with 21 points, his 31st straight game scoring in double figures, the longest streak in the Atlantic Coast Conference. The Cavaliers (7-2) got back on track in John Paul Jones, bouncing back from a 70-68 loss at home Wednesday to Syracuse that was only the second loss there in 23 games. The Cavaliers also have won their last 19 games against in-state opponents, dating back to the 1997-98 season. Adrian Joseph had his fourth double-double of the season, with 13 points and 10 rebounds. Mamadi Diane and Calvin Baker each added 11, as the Cavaliers handed the Lancers (2-9) their eighth straight loss. Mike Scott pulled down 11 rebounds for Virginia, which outrebounded the Lancers 49-31. "I've always had a niche for rebounding," Scott said. "Adrian and I battle before every game to see who can come up with the most rebounds." Longwood scored eight points in the opening minutes of the second half to come to within four, but the Lancers turned the ball over five times in a row and Virginia scored 16 unanswered points sparked by back-to-back 3-pointers by Joseph. Another 13-2 run gave Virginia its largest lead of the game, 67-41, with 3:45 remaining. Longwood jumped on the board first, going up 3-0 in the first 1 1/2 minutes, but the Cavaliers responded with a 16-3 run. Back-to-back 3-pointers by Ryan Bogan and Kirk Williams kicked off a 10-2 run by Longwood that brought the Lancers to within three with 3:25 left to play in the half. Virginia took a 29-22 lead into the locker room. Williams was 4-for-7 from the 3-point line, finishing with 20 points for Longwood. Bogan added three 3-pointers and had 11 points. "We've got to keep practicing and keep working together," Bogan said. "We've got to keep depending on each other and good things will start to happen for us. We can't just get down on ourselves. We've got to keep pushing for something better." Longwood shot just 28 percent on the night, compared to nearly 45 percent shooting for Virginia. Still, Leitao said he was disappointed with his team's defense and 21 turnovers. He's hoping back-to-back practices during the next week and a half will help. "We've got a lot of work to do to get better, and we've got a short time to do it in," Leitao said. "We have got to sharpen ourselves in a number of areas, and when and if we do that, we'll start the process of getting better. But now we've got a whole lot to get better at."
